<section class="hero">
  <h1>Everything you’d expect.<br />A few things you wouldn’t.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Eleven does the chat things properly, then adds a few things no other
    messenger has. The full list, in plain words.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" aria-label="The basics">
  <h2>The chat things, done properly</h2>
  <ul class="cards">
    <li>
      <h3>Groups and one-to-ones</h3>
      <p>
        A space for your whole crowd, groups inside it for every topic, and
        private chats when it’s just the two of you.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Photos, videos, and files</h3>
      <p>
        Share pictures and clips that look great and open fast. Photos leave
        out where they were taken — location details are stripped before
        anything leaves your device.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Reactions, replies, and threads</h3>
      <p>
        React with any emoji, reply to exactly the message you mean, and split
        side conversations into their own threads.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Edit and delete</h3>
      <p>
        Typos happen. Fix a message after you’ve sent it, or take it back
        entirely.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>GIFs and link previews</h3>
      <p>
        Search GIFs right from the message box, and see a tidy preview card
        when someone posts a link.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>See who’s around</h3>
      <p>
        A quiet dot shows who’s online. Typing indicators too.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" aria-label="Cross-device and comfort">
  <h2>Made for real life</h2>
  <ul class="cards">
    <li>
      <h3>Everywhere you are</h3>
      <p>
        Any browser, a native Mac app, and an iPhone app. Start on one
        device, pick up on another — what you’ve read stays read everywhere.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>One tap to sign in</h3>
      <p>
        No passwords. Your device signs you in the way it unlocks itself, and
        one sign-in opens every space you belong to.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Call people what <em>you</em> call them</h3>
      <p>
        Rename anyone just for yourself — your &ldquo;Mum&rdquo; can stay
        &ldquo;Carol&rdquo; to everyone else. Your names follow you into
        notifications and mentions.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Notifications that respect you</h3>
      <p>
        You get pinged when someone writes to you — never by marketing,
        never by your own messages, never while you’re already reading.
        Notifications unlock on your device, so they stay private in transit.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Make it yours</h3>
      <p>
        Six themes from warm dusk to cool lagoon, light and dark, and a text
        size that suits your eyes.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Feels native, weighs nothing</h3>
      <p>
        The iPhone app is smaller than a single photo. The Mac app is a
        15&nbsp;MB download. Neither will hog your battery or your disk.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" aria-label="Beyond chat">
  <h2>More than chat</h2>
  <ul class="cards">
    <li>
      <h3>Little apps, right in the chat</h3>
      <p>
        Shared to-do lists, and reminders that nudge the group at the right
        moment. Built in, not bolted on.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Apps built by asking</h3>
      <p>
        Ask for &ldquo;a packing list for the trip&rdquo; or &ldquo;a habit
        tracker&rdquo; and a small app appears in your space, made just for
        your group. No app store, no accounts, no ads.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Helpers on a schedule</h3>
      <p>
        &ldquo;Send us a news round-up every morning.&rdquo; &ldquo;Remind
        everyone about training on Thursdays.&rdquo; Set up helpers that work
        for your group, and only your group.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Eleven, the helper</h3>
      <p>
        Every space comes with Eleven — a built-in helper that answers
        questions, sets things up, and builds those little apps for you. Ask
        it anything.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" aria-label="Running a space">
  <h2>Your space, your rules</h2>
  <ul class="cards">
    <li>
      <h3>A place of your own</h3>
      <p>
        Every space is its own little world with its own address — not an
        account in someone else’s system. No directory, no discovery, no
        strangers wandering in.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Invites, not sign-ups</h3>
      <p>
        The only way in is a link from someone already inside. Same security
        model as your front door.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open groups and access levels</h3>
      <p>
        Let members discover and join groups inside your space, or keep some
        behind an access level — members, committee, family only. You decide.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Charge for membership, if you like</h3>
      <p>
        Running a club or a community? Put a price on an access level and
        members subscribe — 90/10 split, paid into your own Stripe account.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Safe for kids</h3>
      <p>
        A grown-up runs the space and decides who’s in it. There’s no feed,
        no follower counts, and nothing designed to keep anyone scrolling.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Yours to move</h3>
      <p>
        Don’t want anyone hosting your chat — even us? Run Eleven on your
        own machine. It’s one small program, and
        <a href="/self-host/">it’s designed to make that easy</a>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="attrs feature-group" id="eleven-is" aria-label="What Eleven is">
  <h2>Eleven is&hellip;</h2>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Familiar and easy</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        You shouldn’t have to learn how Eleven works. Click a link and
        you’re chatting. It’s one click to save your chats so you don’t
        lose them: no signup required.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Open</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven is not run by a corporation or a big organisation. Get started
        easily if you’re invited to an existing space through the Eleven apps.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Secure</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        In a world where too many apps end up &ldquo;not secure&rdquo;, Eleven
        is designed to be &ldquo;secure enough&rdquo;. The basic principle is:
        if the server got hacked, nothing on the server should expose
        anything. And that’s how it is. Private chats are completely secret to
        the two participants, group chats are secret to the group. That’s it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Web-based</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven stores messages on a server on the web. This allows freedom to
        use Eleven on different devices. Browser window? Check. PWA with push
        notifications? Check. Eleven doesn’t shy away from being a web
        application.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Native</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Even though Eleven is entirely web-based, starting with iOS and Mac,
        Eleven’s apps are native where it matters: in the feels. They’re fast,
        quick to download, and don’t hog your system resources.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Tracking-free</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        There are no trackers associated with Eleven at all. Anything that
        personally identifies you remains secret. That’s it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>AI-enabled</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Frustratingly, all of the above attributes mean that no corporation
        has so far been compelled to produce an app like Eleven, with
        world-class user experience, and absolute respect for the human using
        the product. AI enables the production of the kind of product that we
        wish big tech had, at a fraction of the cost.
      </p>
      <p>
        Eleven is built with the latest AI models, and audited by them too,
        including a security review by Claude&nbsp;Fable. We’re in beta with
        the source open, so nobody has to take our word for any of that. Check
        the code yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Additionally, AI agents can optionally be added to Eleven to do some
        interesting (or stranger) things.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

